body_text.text:
The explosion limits of the H2
 + O2 reaction have been studied thoroughly, and these limits exhibit an interesting variation with pressure. At low pressures, the reaction is stable because radicals diffuse to the walls of the chamber and prevent chain branching, which leads to an explosion. At very high pressure, radical quenching by diffusion to the walls is slowed down, and the heat released by the reaction leads to a thermal explosion (Fig. 18.8
).
